  "prompt": "What type of order should I place for a stock that is expected in to increase sharply?",
  "response": "If you expect a stock to increase sharply, you may consider placing the following types of orders:\n\n1. **Market Order:** This type of order is executed immediately at the current market price. It ensures that you enter the stock position quickly, but there may be slight variations in the expected price due to market fluctuations.\n\n2. **Limit Order:** A limit order allows you to specify the maximum price you're willing to pay for the stock. If the stock price reaches your limit price, the order is executed. This can help you avoid paying more than intended, but there's a risk that the order might not be executed if the stock price doesn't reach your limit.\n\n3. **Stop-Limit Order:** This type of order combines elements of both stop orders and limit orders. You set a stop price at which the order becomes a limit order to buy at your specified limit price or better. This can potentially help you enter a position close to your target price as the stock price rises.\n\n4. **Trailing Stop Order:** A trailing stop order sets a stop price at a specific percentage or dollar amount below the current market price. As the stock price increases, the stop price adjusts accordingly. If the stock price falls by the specified amount, the trailing stop order will execute as a market order.\n\n5. **Buy Stop Order:** You set a stop price above the current market price, indicating that if the stock reaches the stop price, a market order will be executed. This can be useful if you want to ensure you enter the stock only once upward momentum has been confirmed.\n\nEach type of order involves different risk and execution characteristics, so it's important to choose the one that aligns with your investment strategy and risk tolerance.",
